on shows how literature opens us to the domain of possibility and how metaphor offers philosophical power when we think about freedom and change.This book, written by one of the twentieth century's leading phenomenologists, will interest students in philosophy and in literature. They will value the work particularly for its clarification of concepts and terms that frequently emerge in the contemporary intellectual climate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aLiterature, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aPhenomenology and literature. 0aPhenomenology in literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400822430zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400822430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400822430/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK